(thirdQuint)Escitalopram as a Treatment for Pain in Polyneuropathy.

 Tricyclic antidepressants appear to be the most efficacious treatment of painful polyneuropathy.

 However, these drugs are contraindicated in some patients and a substantial number of patients decline treatment due to side-effects.

 Therefore, effective drugs that are better tolerated are needed.

 Clinical and basic research has demonstrated that drugs with serotonergic action can alleviate neuropathic pain.

 Escitalopram increases serotonin concentration in the central nervous system, suggesting that it might be a potential alternative to current treatments of neuropathic pain.

 The aim of this study is to test if escitalopram would relieve painful polyneuropathy.

 Comparisons: Treatment with 20 mg escitalopram daily will be compared in a cross-over design with placebo.

 Each treatment period will last 6 weeks.

 During the last week of each treatment period, the dose will be tapered.

